				Use summation notation to write a formula for the nth equation for the given pattern.







\begin{array}{ccr}
1 &=& 1 \cdot 1 \\
1 + 5 &=& 2 \cdot 3 \\
1 + 5 + 9 &=& 3 \cdot 5 \\
1 + 5 + 9 + 13 &=& 4 \cdot 7 \\
\end{array}	



\sum_{i=0}^n (4i+1) = (n+1) \cdot (2n+1)







\begin{array}{rccr}
(n=2) & \dfrac{1}{1 \cdot 2} &=& \dfrac{1}{2} \\
(n=3) & \dfrac{1}{1 \cdot 2} + \dfrac{1}{2 \cdot 3} &=& \dfrac{2}{3}\\
(n=4) & \dfrac{1}{1 \cdot 2} + \dfrac{1}{2 \cdot 3} + \dfrac{1}{3 \cdot 4} &=& \dfrac{3}{4} \\
(n=5) & \dfrac{1}{1 \cdot 2} + \dfrac{1}{2 \cdot 3} + \dfrac{1}{3 \cdot 4} + \dfrac{1}{4 \cdot 5} &=& \dfrac{4}{5}
\end{array}



\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{1}{i \cdot (i+1)} = \frac{n}{n+1}

An L-shaped triomino is a 2 \times 2 tile with one square missing. It looks like this:



\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.25] %mathbook width=20%
\draw (0,0) -- (0,2) -- (2,2) -- (2,1)--  (0,1) -- cycle;
\draw (0,0) -- (1,0) -- (1,2);
\end{tikzpicture}








